ile appender that writes to the shared volume, then have Filebeat read from that same location. I should keep the console output intact and just add file logging alongside it. Actually, the simpler approach is to use Filebeat with a hostPath mount to read container logs directly from the kind cluster's `/var/log/pods/` directory, which avoids modifying Elasticsearch configuration altogether. Since kind stores logs at a predictable path, Filebeat can read them with the container input type, though I'll need to ensure it has the right permissions to access those files.\n\nFor the version compatibility, I'm going with Beats 8.11.1 to match the source Elasticsearch cluster, and while the monitoring cluster is on 7.17.9, it should handle the data format fine since ES 7.17 is backward compatible with Beats 8.x output.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider whether Metricbeat 7.17.9 can even collect from ES 8.11.1 — the monitoring APIs like `_nodes/stats` and `_cluster/stats` should work across versions, but I'm not entirely sure about the `_monitoring/bulk` endpoint compatibility.\n\nLet me think through the authentication piece: ES 8.11.1 enforces security by default, so I'll need to configure Metricbeat with username and password credentials over SSL. Version 7.17.9 definitely supports this.\n\nAlright, I'm going with Metricbeat 7.17.9 and Filebeat 7.17.9 for the monitoring setup. Now I'll start building out the actual configuration files, beginning with the Metricbeat ConfigMap that specifies the Elasticsearch module with xpack monitoring enabled.\n\nWriting Metricbeat config... Adding sidecar containers... I'm setting up the resource limits and security context for the Filebeat container, then mounting the config file and pod logs. Now I need to figure out how to update both StatefulSets—I'm thinking through whether to use `kubectl patch` or `kubectl apply`, keeping in mind that changes will trigger a rolling update of the pods.\n\nLooking at the StatefulSet configurations